## 2. Structural Divergence Metric

### 2.1 Definition

Define a **structural divergence function** Φ(t) that quantifies deviation from the previous stable hierarchical configuration.

**Requirements:**
- Φ(t) = 0 immediately after structural reset
- Φ(t) grows monotonically during structural evolution
- Φ(t) spikes sharply at phase transitions
- Φ(t) computable in O(N) or O(N log N) time

### 2.2 Construction via Observable Metrics

We construct Φ(t) as a weighted combination of fast-computable structural indicators:

```
Φ(t) = Σᵢ wᵢ Δᵢ(t)
```

where Δᵢ(t) are normalized changes in structural metrics, and wᵢ are weights (Σwᵢ = 1).

**Candidate metrics:**

**1. Virial ratio** (exact kinetic, sampled potential):
```
Q(t) = 2K(t) / |U(t)|

where:
K(t) = Σᵢ (1/2) mᵢ |vᵢ|²              [O(N)]
U(t) ≈ (N/S) Σᵢ Σⱼ∈S(i) G mᵢ mⱼ / |rᵢ - rⱼ|   [O(N) via sampling]
```

S(i) = random sample of √N neighbors of particle i  
S = sample size = √N

**Normalized divergence:**
```
Δ_Q(t) = |Q(t) - Q(t₀)| / Q(t₀)
```

**2. Escape velocity distribution:**
```
v_esc = √(2|U|/M)

f_esc(t) = (1/N) Σᵢ 𝟙(|vᵢ| > 0.8 v_esc)   [O(N)]

Δ_esc(t) = |f_esc(t) - f_esc(t₀)|
```

**3. Binding energy distribution:**

For each particle i, compute binding to nearest massive neighbor:

```
Eᵦ(i) = min_{j≠i} [-G mᵢ mⱼ / |rᵢ - rⱼ|]   [O(N) per particle, O(N²) total]
```

To reduce to O(N): sample nearest neighbors or use spatial hashing.

**Kolmogorov-Smirnov statistic between distributions:**
```
Δ_KS(t) = sup_x |F_Eb(x,t) - F_Eb(x,t₀)|   [O(N log N) with sorting]
```

**4. Center-of-mass variance:**
```
R_com² = Σᵢ mᵢ |rᵢ - r_cm|² / M   [O(N)]

Δ_com(t) = |R_com²(t) - R_com²(t₀)| / R_com²(t₀)
```

### 2.3 Combined Structural Divergence

```
Φ(t) = w_Q Δ_Q(t) + w_esc Δ_esc(t) + w_KS Δ_KS(t) + w_com Δ_com(t)
```

**Recommended weights** (empirically tuned):
```
w_Q = 0.3,  w_esc = 0.2,  w_KS = 0.4,  w_com = 0.1
```

**Computational complexity:** O(N log N) dominated by KS statistic

With approximate KS or less frequent computation: **O(N) amortized**

