## 6. Optimality Result

### Theorem 1: Structural Monitoring Lower Bound

**Claim:** Any algorithm that accurately tracks hierarchical structure must compute at least O(N) operations per timestep on average.

**Proof sketch:**

Structural metrics (virial ratio, energy distribution, etc.) are global properties requiring information from all N particles. Any computation with fewer than O(N) operations cannot access all particle states, therefore cannot detect all relevant phase transitions.

□

### Theorem 2: Asymptotic Equivalence to FMM

**Claim:** For systems with R = o(T_steps), threshold-triggered monitoring achieves same asymptotic cost as FMM.

**Proof:**

```
C_threshold = T_steps × c₁ N + R × c₂ N log N
            = N (c₁ T_steps + c₂ R log N)
            
C_FMM = c₃ N × T_steps

For R = o(T_steps):
  lim_{T→∞} [C_threshold / C_FMM] 
  = lim_{T→∞} [(c₁ T + c₂ R log N) / (c₃ T)]
  = c₁ / c₃
  = Θ(1)
```

Therefore C_threshold = Θ(C_FMM).

□

### Corollary: Bounded Error Advantage

While asymptotic cost is equivalent, threshold-triggered approach achieves:

```
ε_threshold = O(1)  (bounded by τ)
ε_FMM(t) = ε₀ exp(t/λ) → ∞
```

**Result:** Same computational cost, exponentially better long-term accuracy.

